sentence: Crude continues slide on bearish U.S. inventory report .

Investing.com - Oil prices extended Wednesday 's losses into Thursday as investors avoided the commodity on news that U.S. supplies rose more than expected last week , stoking fears the country is awash in crude while soft on demand .
On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light sweet crude futures for delivery in December traded at USD96 .33 a barrel during U.S. trading , down 0.46 % .
The commodity hit a session low of USD96 .05 and a high of USD97 .00 .
The December contract settled down 1.46 % at USD96 .77 a barrel on Wednesday .

The U.S. Energy Information Administration said in its weekly report that U.S. crude oil inventories rose by 4.1 million barrels in the week ended Oct. 25 , well above expectations for an increase of 2.3 million barrels .
Total U.S. crude oil inventories stood at 383.9 million barrels , the highest level since June .
The report also showed that total motor gasoline inventories declined by 1.7 million barrels , compared to expectations for a drop of 140,000 barrels .
U.S. crude prices have slid in recent weeks amid concerns the recent U.S. government shutdown dampened an already lackluster economic recovery and eroded demand in the world 's largest oil consumer .

Curbing losses , however , were bullish regional manufacturing numbers out of the U.S. Data released earlier revealed that the Chicago manufacturing purchasing managers ' index jumped to 65.9 in October from 55.7 in September , its biggest advance in 30 years .
Analysts had expected the index to decline to 55.0 .
The new orders component of the index jumped to a nine-year high of 74.3 from 58.9 in September .
The news rekindled hopes for a more robust U.S. recovery , one that will demand more fuel and energy going forward .

Elsewhere , the Department of Labor said the number of individuals filing for initial jobless benefits in the week ending October 25 declined by 10,000 to a seasonally adjusted 340,000 , in line with market expectations .
Meanwhile on the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for December delivery were down 0.97 % at USD108 .80 a barrel , up USD12 .47 from its U.S. counterpart .
